  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The Catholic Church has traditionally only ordained men as priests and bishops, based on their interpretation of biblical teachings and historical church practices. The Pope, being the Bishop of Rome and head of the Catholic Church, has historically always been male. Some key reasons include:\n\n1. Biblical interpretation: The Church points to Jesus choosing only male apostles and the all-male priesthood in early Christianity.\n\n2. Church tradition: The role has been exclusively male for nearly 2,000 years.\n\n3. Theological arguments: The Catholic Church believes that priests represent Christ, and since Christ was male, priests should be male.\n\nWhile some other Christian denominations have female clergy, the Catholic Church maintains its position of male-only priesthood, including the papacy. This remains a topic of ongoing discussion and debate within the church.",
